Troubleshooting Swap Usage
When the Linux kernel detects that all memory and all swap are in use, it takes it upon itself to kill the
process that is using the most memory and swap. This usually means MySQL. The kill is not a
graceful shutdown, so when the kernel kills the process (via OOM killer), it's very likely to cause
MySQL table corruption, so when an appliance reports that it's using excessive swap, it's highly
advisable to take action.
Step 1. Determine how much swap is in use.
The `free -m` command shows memory and swap usage.
[root@aio1 em7admin]# free -m
total used free shared buff/cache available
Mem: 5967 4693 270 330 1003 832
Swap: 6015 419 5596
Step 2. Determine which processes are using swap.
The following command lists the top ten processes using the most swap:
for file in /proc/*/status ; do echo "pid $(echo $file | awk -F"/" {'print $3'}):
$(awk '/VmSwap|Name/{printf $2 " " $3}END{ print ""}' $file)"; done | sort -rnk 4 |
head -10
[root@aio1 em7admin]# for file in /proc/*/status ; do echo "pid $(echo $file | awk -F"/" {'print $3'}): $(awk '/VmSwap|Name/{printf $2 " " $3}END{ print ""}'
$file)"; done | sort -rnk 4 | head -10
pid 8589: mysqld 200860 kB
pid 1127: python2.7 36892 kB
pid 9613: node 17976 kB
pid 9422: uwsgi 17592 kB
pid 9513: uwsgi 17588 kB
pid 9514: uwsgi 17588 kB
pid 9515: uwsgi 17588 kB
pid 9516: uwsgi 17588 kB
pid 9517: uwsgi 17588 kB
pid 9518: uwsgi 17460 kB
Usually, the MySQL daemon (mysqld) is using the most swap. If it is using too much swap, then a
restart of the service will free up the space, but usually restarting the other processes in the list will
free up enough swap to keep the system running.
The list of processes will contain vague references that do not tell you exactly which service might be
using them (e.g. "python2.7" above), so use the pid to determine the full process.
[root@aio1 em7admin]# ps -ef | grep 1127
root 1127 1 0 2018 ? 00:21:14 /usr/bin/python2.7 /opt/em7/sladmin/run.py
Step 3. Restart the process (when possible)
If restarting the service that spawned the process will not affect system performance or usability,
restart the service. In the list above, the python process using 36MB of swap space
is /opt/em7/sladmin/run.py, which is a safe process to restart without repercussions to the users or
the platform (it's the web configurator utility).
[root@aio1 em7admin]# systemctl restart em7_sladmin
[root@aio1 em7admin]# free -m
total used free shared buff/cache available
Mem: 5967 4551 340 330 1075 974
Swap: 6015 384 5631
Run `free -m` again to confirm that swap usage has dropped.
Technical Support can assist with determining which processes can be restarted with minimal or no
impact to service. In the list above, `uwsgi` is the ScienceLogic agent collector process, and `node`
processes run the nextui (the new UI that is in beta). If you aren't using either, feel free to restart
their services (uwsgi and nextui, respectively). Run the loop in step 2 to get the list of the next ten
processes and repeat as necessary until swap is reduced.
